Proximity of Philadelphia Schools and Food Sources to Examine Childhood Obesity Risk

BMIN5030 Final Project

Author

Emily Kim

1 Github

https://github.com/emikim/BMIN-5030-Final-Project

2 Overview

This project explores the relationship between Philadelphia school locations and their surrounding food environments to better understand disparities in access to healthy versus unhealthy food sources and how that might relate to childhood obesity. The goal is determine whether schools across Philadelphia are surrounded by more fast food outlets other healthier food options and to examine how this proximity might relate to childhood obesity.

For this project, I am using a couple of publicly available data sets from OpenDataPhilly. These data sets include spatial data on food retailer locations and categories across Philadelphia, which I will integrate with school location data to assess patterns of healthy and unhealthy food access.

For my project, I met with Anita Stief, MPH, RD, LDN, Education Coordinator for the Penn MPH Program, who provided insights into nutrition disparities and food insecurity in Philadelphia. She emphasized that neighborhoods like West and North Philadelphia face limited access to fresh healthy foods and higher rates of diet related diseases compared to areas like Center City. I also met with Jennifer Orr, MSPHS, Project Manager, in MEHP at Penn, who shared her perspective on how socioeconomic factors and school environments influence childrenâs dietary habits and long term health. From these discussions, I learned how nutrition, environment, and policy intersect to shape health inequities across Philadelphia communities.

3 Introduction

Limited access to healthy foods is a long standing public health challenge that contributes to widening health disparities across cities in the United States. In Philadelphia, where you live in the city matters in terms of your health outcomes. Generally, if people live closer to Center City, their health outcomes and factors are better than those who are farther from Center City. Additionally, the distribution of food retailers is highly uneven with many neighborhood lacking fresh produce, but have many outlets to fast food chains and corner stores. These food environments are closely linked to diet quality, body mass index (BMI), and long term disease risk. Children are especially vulnerable because their daily food choices are shaped around their homes and particularly schools, as that is where they spend most of their time. As a result, school proximity to unhealthy food sources can influence students eating behaviors and contribute to childhood obesity, poor nutrition, and chronic diseases later in life. For this project, I was curious about how where you lived in Philadelphia determines your health outcomes, particulary for children and how this relates to food store locations and if this impacts childhood obesity risk. This project addresses the problem by examining whether Philadelphia schools are surrounded more by fast food and corner stores than by healthy food options, and by considering what the pattern might imply for nutrition equity and community health.

Understanding the issue requires approaches that integrate insights from public health, nutrition science, urban planning, and data science. The people I met with explained that access to healthy food in Philadelphia depends on neighborhood geography to an extent and central areas such as Center City have better access to healthier foods and higher life expediencies, whereas the farther neighborhoods are from Center City are more likely to face food insecurity and higher rates of chronic disease. They also stated how socioeconomic disparities and school level factors shape childrenâs dietary choices. Their perspectives highlight how environment, policy, and behavior intersect, reinforcing the need to analyze Philadelphiaâs school food landscape using spatial data and informatics methods to inform equity nutrition policies and intervention design.

Research Questions:

  1. Does proximity to unhealthy food sources differ by geographic region of Philadelphia? Do schools in areas with higher poverty or worse health outcomes have fewer healthy food retailers?
  2. Do disparities in food access align with neighborhood poverty?
  3. What is the relationship between school proximity to food resources and childhood obesity in Philadelphia?

Clean Data

Merged data sets, recoding variables, and filtering.

# Libraries
library(tidyverse)
library(sf)

# Set a common CRS (Pennsylvania South Stateplane, EPSG:2272)
target_crs <- 2272   

schools     <- st_transform(schools,     crs = target_crs)
food_retail <- st_transform(food_retail, crs = target_crs)
walk_access <- st_transform(walk_access, crs = target_crs)
low_no      <- st_transform(low_no,      crs = target_crs)
farmers     <- st_transform(farmers,     crs = target_crs)
wic         <- st_transform(wic,         crs = target_crs)

# Clean SCHOOLS
schools_clean_sf <- schools %>%
  transmute(
    school_id   = location_id,
    school_name = school_name,
    address     = street_address,
    zip         = as.character(zip_code),
    type        = type,
    grade_org   = grade_org,
    enrollment  = enrollment,
    school_level = case_when(
      str_detect(grade_org, regex("Elementary", ignore_case = TRUE)) ~ "Elementary",
      str_detect(grade_org, regex("Middle",     ignore_case = TRUE)) ~ "Middle",
      str_detect(grade_org, regex("High",       ignore_case = TRUE)) ~ "High",
      TRUE ~ "Other"
    )
  )

# Clean FOOD RETAIL (HPSS, LPSS, poverty)
food_retail_clean_sf <- food_retail %>%
  transmute(
    GEOID10,
    area_healthy   = TOTAL_HPSS,
    area_unhealthy = TOTAL_LPSS,
    area_total     = TOTAL_HPSS + TOTAL_LPSS,
    healthy_ratio  = if_else(
      TOTAL_HPSS + TOTAL_LPSS > 0,
      TOTAL_HPSS / (TOTAL_HPSS + TOTAL_LPSS),
      NA_real_
    ),
    pct_poverty       = PCT_POVERTY,
    high_poverty_raw  = HIGH_POVERTY,
    pct_vehicle_avail = PCT_VEHICLE_AVAILABILITY,
    geometry
  )

# Clean WALK ACCESS + LOW/NO ACCESS
walk_access_clean_sf <- walk_access %>%
  transmute(
    GEOID = GEOID,
    walk_access_status = ACCESS_,
    geometry
  ) %>%
  st_make_valid()

low_no_clean_sf <- low_no %>%
  transmute(
    GEOID = GEOID,
    low_no_access_status = ACCESS_,
    geometry
  ) %>%
  st_make_valid()

# Real HEALTHY POINTS: Farmers + WIC
farmers_fixed_sf <- farmers %>%
  mutate(zip = as.character(zip))

wic_fixed_sf <- wic %>%
  mutate(zip = as.character(zip))

healthy_all_points <- bind_rows(
  farmers_fixed_sf %>% mutate(type = "Farmers"),
  wic_fixed_sf      %>% mutate(type = "WIC")
) %>%
  select(type, geometry)

# Spatial joins: attach neighborhood context to SCHOOLS

# Schools + food retail (HPSS / LPSS / poverty)
schools_with_retail <- schools_clean_sf %>%
  st_join(food_retail_clean_sf, join = st_within)

# Add walk access
schools_with_walk <- schools_with_retail %>%
  st_join(walk_access_clean_sf, join = st_within)

# Add low/no access
schools_with_access <- schools_with_walk %>%
  st_join(low_no_clean_sf, join = st_within)

# Count nearby healthy points within ~10-min walk (~800 ft)
school_buffers_10 <- schools_with_access %>%
  st_buffer(dist = 800)   # ~10-minute walk

healthy_counts_10 <- school_buffers_10 %>%
  st_join(healthy_all_points, join = st_intersects) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  group_by(school_id) %>%
  summarize(
    n_healthy_10 = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

# Final MERGED DATA
merged_data <- schools_with_access %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  left_join(healthy_counts_10, by = "school_id") %>%
  mutate(
    high_poverty = case_when(
      high_poverty_raw %in% c(1, "1", "Yes", "YES", "yes") ~ 1,
      high_poverty_raw %in% c(0, "0", "No",  "NO",  "no")  ~ 0,
      TRUE ~ NA_real_
    ),
    has_healthy_10 = case_when(
      is.na(n_healthy_10) ~ NA_real_,
      n_healthy_10 == 0   ~ 0,
      n_healthy_10 > 0    ~ 1
    )
  ) %>%
  select(
    school_id,
    school_name,
    address,
    zip,
    type,
    school_level,
    enrollment,
    area_healthy,
    area_unhealthy,
    area_total,
    healthy_ratio,
    pct_poverty,
    high_poverty,
    pct_vehicle_avail,
    walk_access_status,
    low_no_access_status,
    n_healthy_10,
    has_healthy_10
  )

No individual level cohort was used and I examined the structural food environment and socioeconomic factors that contribute to childhood obesity risk around schools. But there were ~250 elementary, ~80 middle, ~120 high, and ~40 other (mixed program/special) schools.

area_healthy = number of high produce stores (HPSS)
area_unhealthy = number of low produce / corner type stores (LPSS)
area_total = HPSS + LPSS
healthy ratio = HPSS / (HPSS+LPSS)\

The merged data shows basic school information, neighborhood food environments, socioeconomic context, access context, and nearby healthy outlets. All spatial datasets were converted to a commom CRS (PA South State EPSG 2272) so that distances and spatial joins were accurate. The schools dataset was cleaned to keep key fields (school ID, name, level, enrollment) and to categorize each school as Elementary, Middle, or High.

Food retail data were simplified into analysis-ready indicators: counts of healthy stores (HPSS), unhealthy stores (LPSS), total stores, and a healthy food ratio (HPSS Ã· [HPSS + LPSS]). Neighborhood context variablesâincluding poverty percentage, high-poverty status, and vehicle availabilityâwere retained.

Walk-access and low/no-access datasets were validated and spatially joined to each school. Farmers markets and WIC offices were combined into a single layer of healthy-food locations. For each school, an 800-foot buffer (approx. 10-minute walk) was used to count nearby healthy food points.

All layers were merged through sequential spatial joins, producing one comprehensive dataset per school containing neighborhood poverty, food retailer mix, healthy food ratio, walk-access status, and counts of healthy food sources. This final cleaned dataset was used for mapping, descriptive statistics, clustering, and regression analyses.

Neighborhood poverty was defined using the City of Philadelphiaâs classification of census tracts in which at least 30% of households live below the federal poverty line. Each school was assigned the poverty status of its surrounding census tract through spatial joining, providing a measure of the socioeconomic environment students experience around their school.

Childhood Obesity Risk Score

library(dplyr)

risk_data <- merged_data %>%
  mutate(
    # normalize predictors so they are comparable
    z_unhealthy = scale(area_unhealthy),
    z_poverty   = scale(pct_poverty),
    z_healthy   = scale(1 - healthy_ratio), # higher = worse
    
    # weighted composite (weights based on literature)
    obesity_risk_score = 
        0.4 * z_poverty +
        0.4 * z_unhealthy +

Then, I created a childhood obesity risk score that combined environmental and socioeconomic factors known to increase childhood obesity risk: poverty, (pct_area), unhealthy food density (area_unhealthy), and lack of healthy food availability (healthy_ratio). Each variable was scaled and weighted based on public health evidence from literature (poverty = strong predictor 0.4, unhealthy stores = strong predictor 0.4, and low healthy access = moderate predictor 0.2)

z_unhealthy = standardized number of unhealthy stores
z_poverty = standardized poverty
z_healthy = standardized lack of healthy stores
obesity_risk_score = z_unhealthy + z_poverty + z_healthy

A higher score = worse food environment + higher childhood obesity risk
A lower score = healthier food environment + lower childhood obesity risk
Around 0 = average risk
Positive scores = above average risk
Negative scores = below average risk

Childhood obesity risk scores ranged from -2.22 to +2.41 across Philadelphia schools. Schools with above +1 represented the high risk environments, characterized by high poverty, unhealthy food retailers, and limited access to food. Most schools fell in between -0.5 and +0.5, indicating moderate risk but still limited healthy food availability.

Clustering of School Food Environments

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

# Start from risk_data and add a row_id so we can track rows
risk_data2 <- risk_data %>%
  mutate(row_id = dplyr::row_number())

# Build clustering input with row_id, then drop NAs
cluster_input <- risk_data2 %>%
  select(
    row_id,
    healthy_ratio,
    area_unhealthy,
    pct_poverty,
    n_healthy_10
  ) %>%
  tidyr::drop_na()

# Scale only the numeric columns (not row_id)
cluster_mat <- cluster_input %>%
  select(-row_id) %>%
  scale()

# Run k-means on the complete cases
set.seed(123)
k3 <- kmeans(cluster_mat, centers = 3)

# Attach cluster labels back to the clustering dataframe
cluster_input$cluster <- k3$cluster

# Join cluster labels back to the full risk_data2 by row_id
risk_data2 <- risk_data2 %>%
  left_join(
    cluster_input %>%
      select(row_id, cluster),
    by = "row_id"
  )

      y = area_unhealthy,

Cluster 1 schools had the highest healthy food ration (mean 0.33) and the lowest density of unhealthy retailers (mean 21.8) as well as the lowest mean poverty (mean 12%). This represents the most nutritious and resource-rich school environments.

Cluster 2 = moderate risk environments
Cluster 2 showed moderately low healthy food availability (mean = 0.11) and elevated unhealthy food density (mean = 28.0) with moderate poverty levels (mean = 19%), indicating transitional neighborhoods with mixed food access.

Cluster 3 = high risk environments (worse food areas)
Cluster 3 contained the most disadvantaged school environments, with the lowest healthy food ratio (mean = 0.08), the highest number of unhealthy retailers (mean = 51.7), and the highest poverty rates (mean = 47%).
These areas represent neighborhoods with substantially elevated childhood obesity risk due to concentrated structural disadvantages and limited healthy food access.

These clusters align geographically with known disparities. Cluster 3 schools are assumed to be concentrated farther from Center City which are areas with higher chronic disease burden and lower life expectancy.

6 Limitations

The project is limited by the absence of Philadelphia specific childhood obesity data, the constrains of available spatial health outcomes, and the fact that food environment data sets measure geographic availability rather true affordability, accessibility, or quality.

I tried so far to find data sets about childhood obesity in Philadelphia and thought there would be at least something I can use in all of the data sets I am using (because I used a lot sources), but I couldnât find anything so I used national data instead to make conclusions. So although childhood obesity could not be mapped directly, national obesity trends and local environment indicators were used to infer potential risk. A direct regression between school environments and childhood obesity was not possible because no Philadelphia childhood dataset could be found. Instead, I created an environmental obesity risk score and used regression to identify which neighborhood features predict obesogenic school environments. Poverty and unhealthy food density were the strongest predictors. National childhood obesity trends are increasing, and we can assume from this that Philadelphia childhood obesity risk is increasing as well.

Healthy food sources may be undercounted because healthy food environments relied on farmers markets, WIC locations, and high produce supply stores (HPSS). Farmers markets operate seasonally, WIC locations serve as more administrative rather than retail roles, and HPSS classifications may not capture the full range of healthy food access (eg. food cop-ops, specialty markets).

The food environment datasets indicate the presence of food outlets, but do not represent price differences, quality of available produce, store hours of reliability, and cultural relevance of food options. With this, the true accessibility of healthy foods may differ from what spatial data suggests.

7 Conclusion

This project examined the food environments surrounding Philadelphia schools and identified substantial spatial inequities in access to healthy vs unhealthy food sources. By integrating multiple data sets like neighborhood food retail, farmers markets, WIC offices, school locations, poverty indicators, walk ability measures, and national trends in childhood obesity, the analysis demonstrated the majority of Philadelphia schools are situated in environments that may increase children risk for obesity and poor nutrition.

Quantitative findings reveal disparities. Over 91% of schools are located in neighborhoods where healthy food retailers make up less than 25% of all food outlets. Schools in high poverty neighborhoods have a 40% lower healthy food ration (9.9% vs 15.7%) and 40% more unhealthy food retailers compared to schools in lower poverty neighborhoods. These patterns presume that students in disadvantaged areas are disproportionately surrounded by corner stores, fast food outlets, and other low produce stores, while having limited access to fresh fruits, vegetables, and nutritious options. Such environmental inequities mirror national trends showing rising childhood obesity and underscore how local food environments may reinforce broader health disparities.

Although direct neighborhood level childhood obesity data for Philadelphia was not available, the integration of food availability, walkability, poverty, and life expectancy data provides meaningful insight into the structural conditions shaping childrenâs health risks. Planning districts farther from Center City - areas with lower health food availability - also showed lower life expectancy, suggesting to socioeconomic disadvantage, limited healthy food access, and more poor long term health outcomes.

Overall, we can conclude that children in schools farther from Center City may face risk for higher risks for childhood obesity, poverty, and lower life expectancy. This analysis demonstrated that Philadelphiaâs school food environments are characterized by substantial inequities that align with known risk factors for childhood obesity. Improving access to healthy foods around schools through policy interventions, urban planning, community partnerships, or expansions of programs like WIC and farmers markets, represents a critical opportunity to support healthier environments for children and reduce preventable nutrition related disparities across the city.
